segments.text: Testing, testing, testing, one, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.

This is December 15th, and we're in San Antonio, and I have the joy and pleasure of chatting with an old friend, Clark Munro, who spells his last name M-U-N-R-O-E. As far as we know, we are not related.
And to begin with, Clark, would you introduce yourself
to this tape or the transcription, anyone who would read it, describe family background, where you grew up.
Tell a biographical summary before you got to Texas A&M the first time.
All right.
I was raised in Pennsylvania, small town, 250 people.
One of four children, three boys and a girl.
My father was a small town banker.
We lived there until World War II started.
He was commissioned in the Army during World War II.
He'd been at World War I.
And he ended up coming to San Antonio as a major in the Air Force.
He informed us that he was too old to go overseas.
So he said to my mother, sell the house and bring the kids and come on down here.
My older brother was in his first year at BMI.
And at that time, we drove down on four black market tires that we had to get in order to make the trip.
And the day we arrived, he got ordered overseas.
And he left before we had any furniture in the house or really knew where we were.
And they stayed here then the rest of their lives.
I ended up going into the Navy after I graduated from high school in 1943.
I finished one year of high school here in San Antonio.
I spent three years in the Navy, got out.
None of my family had ever gone to college.
I guess I was one of the generation that, because of the GI Bill, had that opportunity.
And I had no idea about colleges in Texas.
My family, without any background in college-level education, weren't in any position to
give me much advice.
I happened to be running into a classmate, a high school classmate of mine, after I got out of Navy, and he said, where are you going to go to college?
And I said, I haven't any idea.
And he said, well, I'm going to go to A&M.
You want to go there?
And I said, where is it?
And he said, well, I've got us a ride.
At that time, there weren't many cars, and certainly in college, you didn't have cars.
And he said, we've got an extra space you want to ride up with, so I packed a suitcase and joined three other guys and we drove up to A&M and that was my introduction to Texas A&M.
And did you say you had finished high school?
I did finish high school.
Which high school?
Alma-Hines.
Alma-Hines.
Alright, when you go to A&M, that's the fall of what year?
Okay, there was one interlude in there and this bears on when I got there.
My family was on a ranch up in Waco for the summer when I got out of the Navy.
And when I was up, so I reported there after I got out of the Navy.
I went to a, I think it was a semester or a quarter at Baylor in summer school and got some credits there.
So I didn't come into A&M until the fall of 47.
Yeah.
You had never visited.
Never, didn't know the place existed.
Had you even applied?
No.
How did you get admitted?
I had a high school diploma, and it's my understanding, at least from this perspective, all you had to do was show up on the campus with a high school diploma, and you could get in.
You were better.
Describe those first few days.
How did you get located into a place to live and registration and so forth?
Well, this friend of mine, and his name was John Drisdale,
And John and I are still great friends.
You were all freshmen?
We were all freshmen.
And he had been there before.
He knew about the school.
He had been there before.
And I don't remember what circumstances.
But we just showed up and registered.
And they gave us a room.
And he and I roomed together.
Where was registration?
Do you remember?
I really don't remember.
I think it may have been Sabisa Hall.
It had to have been Sabisa Hall, because I was over, I was in, I did not go into the core initially, and so all of us, it was Sabisa Hall, I remember now.
Do you remember what you took that first semester?
I enrolled, my major was going to be business, and I just presumed it was just general business courses.
I had
It wasn't very well planned.
I just decided business was a good thing to take, and I decided to take it.
And I'm always glad I did.
It was a good education.
And where did you room that first time?
I'm trying to think of the dorm number.
It was there right as you go into Northgate on the right.
Of course, at that time, that had always been core dormitories in there.
The non-core people, the vets, were in there at that time,
And I honestly don't remember the name of the dorm, it was down at the end of the little rectangle.
Alright, and as an old veteran, you were how old?
I must have been all of, let's see, 20, maybe 19, 20.
Yeah, I must have been about 20.
And your Baylor courses made you basically, though, taking introductory courses, freshman courses that first year.
That's right.
Describe getting settled into the dormitory.
What was in your room?
What was the routine?
Number one is for the newer people, they were not air conditioned.
There were no telephones.
It was a bare bones room.
It had a double bunk, two tables, two chairs, and that was it.
And my roommate and I, it was kind of hot.
And together we scraped up enough money to go down to Montgomery Wards and finance electric fans
which, as I remember, was at about $30.
And later on, we decided we needed a radio, and so we went back down to Montgomery Wards and financed a radio.
And as long as we were roommates, we kept that, and when we split, when I went into the Corps, we flipped a coin, and I got the fan, and he got the radio.
It wasn't very fancy, but it served.
The financing of this year, was it entirely GI Bill?
Entirely GI Bill.
Not long after I went to A&M, I started to work.
I got a job down at WTOW.
The college owned the station at that time.
And the studios, if you can call them that, were on the top floor of the administration building.
And so I worked jobs as a disc jockey down there.
I remember I was interviewed and the fellow that interviewed me put me in front of a microphone and he said, imagine that you're
announcing a golf match, and how would you broadcast a golf match?

Well, I didn't play golf, but I'd seen enough of it that I stumbled my way through about five minutes of that, and he said, you're hired, and I made, I think, 50 cents an hour, and I had this jockey show for about a year and a half.
How many hours per night or week?
Not, maybe four hours a day.
And then on the weekends, maybe more than that.
What time did you play?
I think it varied because we're all students and we just worked around our classes.
And what kind of music did you play?
Anything, but the most interesting music, I had a disc jockey show at 1230, and my theme song was a Grandpa Jones record called Hear Rattler.
And in that song, Grandpa Jones, about halfway through it,
would call his dog and be, hey Rattler, hey Rattler.

The troops loved this and of course that was before there was any air conditioning and all the windows were open in the dorms and the seniors would make the freshmen stick their heads out the window and call, hey Rattler, when my program came on.
So it made my reputation at A&M, at least at that year.
Did you have a distinctive
name for your program?
It was the Clark Monroe Show.
Okay.
My name got around the campus pretty quick.
And the distance that WTAW could carry then, do you know?
I don't think that much beyond Brazos County.
I don't remember how many watts we had, maybe 5,000 watts, but nobody else would listen to us but A&M people anyway, and at that time there was no other station.
KORA was not in existence at that time.
That was the only other
It was the only station in town.
Really?
Yeah.
Did anybody at that point have an explanation of what the letters stood for?
I don't ever remember anyone saying that.
See, today, supposedly, they stand for Watch the Aggies Win.
That's a later edition, I think.
I don't remember that.
We didn't win much back then, either.
What kind of homework did you do to get your records and so forth ready?
Oh, that was simple.
I'd just walk in about 30 minutes ahead of time and pull records and go for 30 minutes if that was the time of my show.
My show was ad lib.
Everything else we had a format that they subscribed to and it was no problem.
Now, Grandpa Jones is country music.
Oh, yeah.
But was it big band mixed in with country?
Oh, yeah.
Not on my show.
My show was mostly country music.
But we did some other things, you know, other times of the day.
Now, had you done radio ever before?
Never been in a radio station of my life.
Back to your room.
What were the furnishings in the room other than the bunk and the table?
That was it.
And how much gear did you take in terms of clothing in that first year?
Oh, very little.
I carried it all in two suitcases.
And I'm sure I may have had one suit, thinking that this is right after the war.
And there wasn't much of that.
You still couldn't buy white shirts unless under the counter.
And I didn't have enough money to buy more than one suit.
So there was plenty of room.
And room left over, yeah.
This was a veteran's dorm.
Yeah, everything, at that time, everybody was in the corps unless you were a veteran.
So this is what we called a non-vet, I mean, a non-corps.
About how many of you, as far as you can recall, about what was the percentage of non-corps, of the vets?
Gosh, I'm sure I knew that at one time, but I would say in 47, probably...
The core was still, I think, in the majority.
And I'm thinking now, probably left out of that calculation, the married students.
Because a lot of vets were married and lived off campus.
But the core was the big bulk.
The core was A&M.
Describe a day of routine for you that first year.
What time did you get up?
What did you do where?
Where did you?
I remember we walked a little far.
The classrooms were down below where the power plant is now.
They were all temporary buildings.
Wooden army barracks type of buildings.
I'd usually get up about maybe seven o'clock.
I ate sabisa.
I always ate sabisa because I didn't have money left to eat anywhere else.
And there wasn't much other places to eat anyway.
And my classes were all down south to power plant.
So I went down there, but then of course when I was working at WTOG, I had to walk down to the administration building.
Now, are you talking about the system administration?
System administration.
The one east, not the old academic.
Not the old academic building, no.
That was my pattern pretty much.
Now, I did have some classes like English and liberal arts classes for up in the academic building.
I don't recall having a science class.
So I think primarily I was in the old barracks down south of the power plant and academic building.
That was it.
Of course, there was no student center.
All right.
And you walked back to eat lunch.
I walked back to eat lunch.
Did you have any free time?
Any unscheduled time?
Not really.
I took a pretty good load all the time.
I think I took at least 18 hours, and then of course working down in WTOW took up the rest of my time.
What did you all do in the evenings after supper?
I'd like to say that we studied, and I'm sure we did some, but I don't recall having been overburdened with study either.
There really wasn't much to do there at that time.
How were you veterans treated by the non-veterans, younger veterans?
There never were any problems.
Of course, you really can break down into the married veterans, the non-married veterans, and then the Corps.
The Corps was, you know, they were physically separated from us, but there was never any problem at all.
They got along well, and a number of guys
The veterans moved on over to the Corps, which is what I did in my junior year.
Now, you all left your doors open, I presume.
Oh, yeah.
Because...
I didn't have, I don't think I had a key.
I maybe did, but I don't remember.
And nothing was ever stolen.
No.
And you left your windows open except when it rained.
Yes.
Very few people had covers.
A couple of, you know, some of the veterans had covers.
I was not one of them.
But if you wanted to go into town, into Bryan, you know, you could find somebody to...
to ride with.
But we hitchhiked back and forth to Bryan too.
There wasn't much in Bryan, that was the only movie.
Other than that, there was the campus theater too.
But we'd want to go in town.
And your roommate became a close friend.
Did you make any other important lasting friendships that first year?
Yeah, none that I've kept up with since then, but in Grizzdale I have.
We used to double date a lot.
We used to come down to San Antonio and we had a couple of girlfriends down there.
But I really didn't make a lot of friends like that that stayed with me until I moved over into the Corps.
During that first semester, what were the events or what other circumstances that
made you think that you had made a good choice, that this is a place that you liked?
Uh, I'll tell you, the thing probably that made me like Indian at that time was I had, coming out of the Navy, I'd been on board a cruiser.
I was in a group, a division on a cruiser.
There were 16 of us that lived in literally almost a closet, you know, stacked more than five bucks high.
and you get used to being with a lot of people in close contact and there's a certain camaraderie that stems from that and I kind of sense that same sort of thing.

When I first got out of the Navy I missed that because I was in town and I didn't know anybody and I almost re-enlisted and went back to the Navy but fortunately I didn't but I think that camaraderie carried over and
I always appreciated that.
Do you remember any of the A&M extracurricular events that fall?
I'm not sure if it was this fall, but it probably was.
Number one, there were not much structured extracurricular activity except athletics.
You know, you had the dorms and the core units and so forth.
That was about it.
But you had Yale practice.
Oh, yeah, we did have Yale practice.
The one that stands out in my mind was one that WTAW sponsored together, I think with the battalion, but I think it was mostly WTAW, that we brought Grandpa Jones down for a concert.
And the only place to have it that we could get into was what was known as the Assembly Hall.
And it was...
Oh, not too far from the grill field.
There was a wooden building, exposed rafters, hot.
And old Grandpa Jones came down.
This was in the summer when it was very hot.
And he was really a young man, but he dressed up like he was an older man.
He had a white mustache glued on, you know, on the hat.
And the troops loved him.
We packed and sent him home.
and it got so hot that old Grandma jumped the bus dash bomb.
But that was, and he sang Hear Rattler, I guess, five times, you know.
And that was a fun thing.
That was a big extracurricular activity.
You and your new student buddies, what about the first football games and Yale practices and things like that?
Oh, we loved them.
Yeah, we, you know,
We kind of got caught up in the way the Corps did it.
We went to everything.
Again, there were no girls there, which makes a big difference.
There was a lot of beer drinking and that type of thing.
All off campus, of course.
The only activities were centered around the Corps.
We just fit in right without any problem with that.
Do you remember where y'all practices were held?
On the steps of Goodwin Hall.
Goodwin or YMCA?
I think it was Goodwin.
Goodwin?
Yeah, because we spilled out on the parade ground.
Yeah, it was Goodwin Hall.
And they weren't on held at midnight, were they?
I don't recall.
Not in my first year or two.
That's what I thought.
But yeah, toward the latter year, because I...
After I worked on W-Town, I went to work on the battalion.
And that was when I got into the Corps.
And the reason I respond to the midnight yell practice thing is because there's been a midnight yell practice up at Fort Worth or Dallas, and it got pretty rough.
And some guys got hurt.
So on the battalion, we occasionally launched off into an ill-thought crusade, and we decided that midnight yell practice off campus wasn't a good thing to do, and we editorialized against it.
That was not a wise thing to do.

I don't know where they've drowned out people now, but at that time, if you upset somebody, they would make arrangements to come into your room in the middle of the night and dump a tub full of water on you.
And as a battalion rider, I was at odds with people occasionally, and I used to get drowned out pretty regularly.
My senior year, I roomed with a corps commander, and he wouldn't sleep on the lower bunk.
I had to sleep on the lower bunk.
So, back to your question, we did have midnight yell practice, and after we editorialized against it,
And I got drowned out several times.
We stopped editorializing against me in that Yale practice.
Describe going to an Aggie football game, that first year or so.
You know, I don't recall, other than maybe going up to Waco, going to football games off campus.
No, on campus.
Oh, on campus.
Oh, okay.
Oh, it was, you know, I don't think it's changed except in numbers.
I don't think it's changed at all.
It was a big event.
Did you veterans stand up?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, sure.
But the interesting thing, at that time, there wasn't an athletic dormitory.
The athletes lived in the units.
I don't know where they go to classes these days, but they went to classes then.
You rub shoulders with all the guys on the team constantly.
Who were the, were there any celebrity stars when you got there?
Not that I remember.
Because they were all, there were a number of veterans in that group, too.
Yeah.
I don't, you know, I can't call the name of somebody in those early days who was a big star.
We really didn't have very good teams, to tell the truth.
I do remember going to, I believe I did make a game in Austin, but...
you know, didn't have much money, so it was kind of hard to travel.
I remember one time we did, now this is after I got in the Corps, we went to a game up in Dallas, and five of us crowded into a Jeep with a canvas top on it.
You know, put five people in a Jeep, it isn't easy.
And that was kind of how we got around, but that was better than hitchhiking.
During that first year, who did you turn to for advice about
Anything?
I don't really recall turning to anybody for advice.
You know, we, when I think of the veterans, had kind of learned to live on our own.
Did you all think of yourselves as comparatively mature?
Older, I don't know about mature, but older.
About the only person that I went to for anything was, there was a
His name will come to me.
A student loan fund, McQuillan, E.E.
McQuillan ran a student loan fund.
And you could walk into E.E.
and, oh, it was Mr. McQuillan, and you could borrow $10 on your signature.
And no interest.
All you had to do was agree to pay it back.
And almost everybody I knew was always in hock to Mr. McQuillan.
But he told me one time, he said, I never lost any money.
So he would be the person I would go to when I needed $10.
All right.
When you were registering, say, for the second or third or fourth semesters, was there someone you turned to for advice on what courses to take or not to take?
No.
We were allowed to pick our own courses.
They said, you have to have these before you graduate.
And we just went and took them.
There was no counseling in that sense.
I'm talking about in the business courses.
Were there some faculty members whose courses you had who became important to you in terms of what you learned?
I'm not talking about necessarily the facts, but what they really taught you?
One man, and at this minute I can't call his name, stood out head and shoulders above everybody else, and he taught geography.
And I don't know why.
Skip's lesson?
Skipper's lesson?
No, no.
Okay.
I know who he is, but he was not my father.
And I don't know that he was there that long.
And I don't know why I was taking geography.
But he made geography come alive.
And we all liked it.
I think the veterans were more critical of the professors than the non-vets.
And you could see that.
And if there was a phoneme, there were some phonemes.
We spotted them pretty quick.
I remember I had an advertising prof that I don't think could find the front door.
A&M wouldn't tolerate someone like that today.
But you have to think that all of a sudden overnight A&M doubled or more.
in its student population, and I don't know where they got the crops to come in from.
But there were some good ones, but there were some .
What about the size of classes?
Size of classes were pretty large, at least it seemed to me they were large.
In the early years, they'd fill a room.
Are you talking about 30, or are you talking about 300?
No, 50, 60, but they couldn't get any more than that in a room.
And in the summertime, when it's not in a condition
And it's a wooden building.
You didn't want any more than that in the room anyway.
But we didn't know anybody.
You know, it had always been us.
And academically, how were those first semesters for you?
I didn't have much problem.
Again, I think I had been exposed to some things, you know, just in living through three years in the Navy, that made things easier for me.
Did anybody ever attempt to...
warn you people like they did the fish, look to your left, look to your right, only one of you will still be here two years from now?
No, the veterans, they didn't do that to us.
We were on our own, and we could do pretty much what we wanted to do.
And there were no special advisors just for y'all?
If there were, I never met one.
Since the MSC wasn't there yet, where did y'all go for a soft drink, for an ice cream cone?
There were, I'm going to dig back in memory now, there were several, I'll call them stands, or almost tiny cafes around.
There was one up in the core area, was it Casey's?
And there were maybe two others around campus that you could go to, and they served hamburgers and hot dogs and coffee and stuff like that.
And you just walked to them, and they were just typical little cafes.
And wasn't there one in the Y?
I don't remember one in Hawaii, but there was the Aggieland, I believe it was Aggieland Inn, which was not too far from Sevesa, across the street, I believe.
And you could get a nice meal in there.
It wasn't very large, and since none of us had any money, we didn't go in there very often.
But it was a place you could take your parents when they came up.
Although my parents never came down to campus, I don't think.
I don't think they ever sat down again.
My mother.
How often did, the first year or so, how often did you come home?
Maybe two or three times, hitchhike, get in the Aggieland.
Now, you didn't have a uniform to wear.
No.
That first year.
Was it easier for the guys in uniform to get a ride than it was for the rest of you?
No, because in the A line, you just walked up and you put your bag down.
There were some guys from the Corps there and some nonvets.
And the people who would stop, they didn't care.
They knew who you were.
What route did you take going back and forth?
Highway 21.
Really?
Yeah, Highway 21.
Normally, how much time did you expect it to take?
Your experience led you to believe it.
To get a ride?
No, no, no, from there to here.
Oh gosh, I don't remember.
Yeah, maybe three or four hours.
So not much longer than that?
No, it's not much longer.
You get picked up quickly.
I mean, unless you were traveling at an off time.
But I'd go out and hit the Aggie line in San Antonio and get to A&M by the same amount of time as I do now.
Where in San Antonio was the best place for an Aggie to get a ride?
It was at Austin Highway.
Austin Highway off of Broadway.
That's always been it.
Used to be.
That why.
Every time you knew where it was.
And if you didn't, someone would tell you.
Share some of the interesting anecdotes you remember from Aggie hitchhiking.
Anytime in your days.
I always had pretty good luck.
I did get with a guy one time that had been drinking and drove too fast.
And I got out.
I forget where I got out.
Round Rock somewhere.
Not Round Rock.
Bastrop.
But, you know, most of the guys would pick you up.
They might be Aggies, or there were parents taking Aggies by them.
So I never had any unusual experiences.
Never worried about it.
Did anybody buy you something to eat?
I don't remember that, no.
We always stopped at Bastrop.
And did they ever offer you a drink?
Never was offered a drink, no.
Any negative experiences?
None whatsoever.
It was so routine.
Nobody thought anything about it.
That's what you said is almost exactly what everybody else has said.
And you didn't hold up a sign.
No.
They knew you were there.
Let's see.
Did you veterans, did they have a nickname for y'all or anything?
No, we were just, I think, non-regs.
I think you call us non-regs.
You were all, even though you were a veteran.
Yeah.
What did you wear to class?
That's a funny question to ask because I don't remember, but I'm sure it wasn't much.
